data.title: Ratings are too nice - all processed
data.text:
The ratings on this place are too nice. If you look at my other 100+ ratings you'll see I'm really generous with my comments, but this is not what the ratings make it out to be. It's simple... this is a old deli that uses completely processed foods. So I could get something proprietary, I asked what they make themselves and their answer was "nothing". 

We were looking for a great hot dog in our new area and instead found a place we'll never return to. 

I'm sure this was a great place "in the day" but it's changed hands a number of times and now it's just a place to avoid.

data.title: Older established eatery
data.text:
Seen the Wednesday special online so decided to give it a go.
Certainly cheap enough, couldn't finish the Rueben and Chicago dog.

data.title: Good Sandwiches and Hot Dogs
data.text: Not inexpensive, but the bread and ingredients are fresh. Parking is plentiful near the westside. Service is good. It is worth a visit.

data.title: Best sandwich in Rancho Cucamonga
data.text: So delicious! Fresh bread, generous size, you'll wonder why this isn't near the top of your lunch circuit. A tad pricey and worth it. Highly recommended.

data.title: Always GOOD
data.text: This is a great deli and the food is always good.  Read the menu ingredients and pick what you like  You will love it.

data.title: I like "Weenie Wednesdays"
data.text:
And so do a lot of other people!

I have lived in Rancho for more than a few years, but I had never been to "The Deli" restaurant.

We went on the so-called "Weenie Wednesdays":  All hot dogs 99 cents--a deal.  The offer a chili dog, sauerkraut, chicago, tex-mex, baked bean and plain.

We had chili dogs conisting of a mild, all-ground meat chile atop a dog (which was just a little larger than the bun) that had been griddled or heated on one of those hot-roller hot dog heaters/cookers.  The chili was decent, the dog had flavor and the dog had not been boiled/steamed to death--the thing was not gigantic, but it had flavor.  

One of us also had a baked bean dog (call it a "beany-weenie"?), which was inhaled quite handily, so I think it was good!  Two of us had the plain with the usual toppings: onions, mustard, relish, etc.  They were supposed to have a jalapeno relish also, but I did not check it out.

All of our dogs were hot, fresh and pretty dang good for a buck each.

We all split an order of--onion rings!  Hot and fresh, they were a little greasy (probably cooked too cold), but it was a huge order of rings and they were fresh. No salt was needed as the salted batter nicely set off the thick rings.

For four of us, cost for dinner?  $11.55 (if I remember correctly, maybe a buck more) for 8 dogs and the onion rings.  Very reasonable and it is supporting a LOCAL business, not a chain--Yea!

We drank water with, but we did note the small but nice collection of bottled beers in the case up front, by the register.

Recommended; I will try to go there again to check out the rest of their menu as the prices seemed very reasonable.
